    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-12-11T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-12-11T03:00:00-05:00" n="446"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d446">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7511: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, [<date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-12-11T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 11, 1935—4 p.m.</date>]<lb/>[Received December 11—9:40
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>218. Embassy’s 213, December 10, 4 p.m. The situation is quiet. Nanking’s
                    decision on the proposed Council presumably awaits appointment of new Cabinet
                    Ministers. There continues to be conflicting reports with regard to the attitude
                    of the Japanese military towards the Council. Doihara is understood to have
                    directed Japanese pressmen not to publish reports with regard to the Japanese
                    attitude.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Students of five local universities including Yenching, Tsing Hua and
                        Peiping National are refusing to attend classes today apparently to show
                        continuing disapproval of the present political situation.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>It is reported that the Association of Educational Institutions at
                        Tientsin issued yesterday a statement opposing autonomy and any impairment
                        of Chinese territorial integrity.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Fighting at Kuyuan is said to have ceased. Repeated to Nanking. By mail to
                        Tokyo.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
